Question: How many days of annual leave am I entitled to each year, and what are
  the rules for carrying unused days over to the following year?
Example answer: Members of staff are entitled to thirty and a half working days of
  paid leave per annum, in addition to the public holidays observed by
  the ECB. At least 20 days must be taken before the end of the
  calendar year, and members of staff may carry over a maximum of 10.5
  days of the annual leave entitlement to the following year. Where
  the minimum 20 days have not been taken by year-end for business or
  personal reasons, the Director General/Director may approve them
  being taken until the end of March of the subsequent year, and the
  Director General Human Resources or their Deputy may approve a
  further unlimited carry-over in exceptional cases on local
  management's justification. (ECB Conditions of Employment, page 13;
  ECB Staff Rules, page 93)
Predicted answer: - Annual leave entitlement per year: The total number of days is not
  specified in the provided excerpt. It refers to Article 27 of the
  Conditions of Employment for the base entitlement. If a full year is
  not worked, the entitlement is pro‑rated and rounded up to the
  nearest half hour (using an average of 21 working days per month).
  - Minimum use within the year: At least 20 days must be taken before
  the end of the calendar year, including at least one period of two
  consecutive weeks.  - Standard carry-over: You may carry over up to
  10.5 days of your annual leave entitlement each year.  - Grace
  period for unmet minimum: If you have not taken the minimum 20 days
