Question: When is a medical certificate required for sick leave?
Example answer: A medical certificate is required when the absence is longer than two
  consecutive working days per period of absence; when a member of
  staff is unable to work the contractually agreed hours due to
  medical reasons; when unable to attend a disciplinary or
  underperformance hearing; when illness or accident occurs during
  annual leave; or when uncertified absences exceed ten working days
  per annum. A single medical certificate can certify an absence of up
  to a maximum of six weeks. (ECB Staff Rules, page 105)
Predicted answer: A medical certificate is required: - for sick leave of two consecutive
  working days or more (Friday+Monday counts; so does Tuesday+Thursday
  when Wednesday is a public holiday); - when you are unable to work
  your contractually agreed hours for medical reasons; - when you are
  unable to attend a disciplinary or underperformance hearing due to
  illness; - when illness or an accident occurs during annual leave; -
  once your uncertified absences exceed 10 working days in a calendar
  year (thereafter); - for any extension of sick leave. Note: The
  ECB’s Medical Adviser may also require a medical certificate for all
  absences.
