Question: My ECB contract ended last month and I am now receiving the
  unemployment allowance. I am pregnant and due in three months — does
  this affect the duration of my entitlement?
Example answer: The standard paid maternity leave for staff is 20 weeks, with four
  additional weeks in case of multiple births. When a former staff
  member in receipt of unemployment benefits gives birth during one of
  the entitlement periods, or is expected to give birth within six
  weeks of the end of such a period, that period is extended by 20
  weeks, with an additional four weeks in the case of multiple births;
  any maternity leave taken immediately preceding the termination of
  the contract is deducted from this extension. (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, pages 13, 18)
Predicted answer: Yes. If you give birth while you are still within your unemployment-
  allowance period (the 60% or the 30% phase), or if your expected due
  date falls within six weeks after that period ends, that period is
  extended by 20 weeks (24 weeks for multiple births). This extension
  can take you beyond the standard two-year cap. If you had taken ECB
  maternity leave immediately before your contract ended, those weeks
  are deducted from the 20/24-week extension. Contact DG HR and
  provide your medical certificate of the expected date to have the
  extension confirmed.
