Question: My spouse, who was an ECB staff member, recently passed away while in
  service. What benefits apply with regard to salary continuation and
  to our return to our country of origin?
Example answer: In the event of the death of a staff member, payment of their salary
  and allowances is extended for three months. Where termination of
  service is caused by death, the resettlement benefits — coverage of
  travel-related expenses and removal of personal belongings, together
  with a resettlement allowance equal to 200% of the monthly basic
  salary for staff entitled to a household allowance or 100% otherwise
  — are paid, under the conditions laid down in the Staff Rules, to
  the surviving spouse or recognised partner or, in their absence, to
  the deceased staff member's dependent children. (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, pages 12, 19)
Predicted answer: - Salary continuation: The ECB will continue paying your late spouse’s
  salary and allowances for three months (Conditions of Employment,
  Art. 37). - Return to country of origin (resettlement):   - As the
  surviving spouse, you (and dependent children, if any) are entitled
  to termination-of-service benefits if you resettle more than 50 km
  from the ECB. These include reimbursement of travel and removal
  (household effects) expenses (Staff Rules 4.2.2).   - If resettling
  outside the EU, reimbursement is capped at the lower of actual costs
  and the cost to the capital of the EU Member State furthest from the
  ECB (Staff Rules 4.2.2).   - If your spouse’s place of recruitment
  was outside the EU, you may request relocation to that place of
  recruitment (Staff Rules 4.2.2).   - Reimbursement of removal
  expenses is made to the surviving spouse/recognised partner or
  dependent children; you must confirm that no similar benefits are or
  will be received from another source (Staff Rules pp. 70, 72). -
  Repatriation of remains: The ECB reimburses the costs to repatriate
  your spouse’s remains to their original place of residence (or, if
  death occurred on official travel, from the place of death to the
  original place of residence or place of employment) (Staff Rules p.
  116).
